Title: শক থেরাপিতে শতাধিক মাকড়সার বিষ সংগ্রহ, তাক লাগালেন বঙ্গসন্তান (Venom collected from hundreds of spiders using shock therapy, a milestone from a son of Bengal)
Notes: The report is about research on spider venom by a team of zoologists. It mentions one death that may have been caused by a spider bite. The junior research fellow in the team may/may not be an arachnologist but possibly not an expert one. The report claims that this researcher has invented a new method using electric shocks (wrongly termed 'shock therapy') to extract venom from spiders. The journalist has possibly not phrased this correctly, as electrical stimulation seems to have been used for this purpose for a long time; however the scientists are quoted as saying that this new method is easy and cheap and will lead to a 'revolution' in spider research. I have scored the article for taxonomic error because Nephila pilipes is spelled wrong (it reads as 'filipes'). Grouping spiders with insects is another error. The spider shown in the photo is not a Nephila but since there is no caption, I haven't scored it for error figures. Although it isn't sensational in the usual way I've scored it for sensationalism because it claims that there are many instances of fingers 'rotting' due to spider bites, and that spiders have been identified as the cause of many deaths.

Title: Beyond the south,Tarantula panic now attacks the north
Notes: Report about fear of tarantulas spreading from south to north Bengal. A resident found a large black hairy fast-moving spider in his garden, which he identified as the same type of tarantula he'd just seen on TV. The local high school biology teacher (it's not clear whether he is an arachnologist) said the spider in the photo looked like a tarantula but he wouldn't give an ID based only on the photo. He advised staying far from the spider, since tarantulas have venom, and even though their bite may not kill, it would cause harm. Though the story is about local panic, no exaggerated claims are made by the writer and the tone is quite restrained.

Title: শক থেরাপিতে শতাধিক মাকড়সার বিষ সংগ্রহ, তাক লাগালেন বঙ্গসন্তান (Venom collected from hundreds of spiders using shock therapy, a milestone from a son of Bengal)
Notes: The report is about research on spider venom by a team of zoologists. It mentions one death that may have been caused by a spider bite. The junior research fellow in the team may/may not be an arachnologist but possibly not an expert one. The report claims that this researcher has invented a new method using electric shocks (wrongly termed 'shock therapy') to extract venom from spiders. The journalist has possibly not phrased this correctly, as electrical stimulation seems to have been used for this purpose for a long time; however the scientists are quoted as saying that this new method is easy and cheap and will lead to a 'revolution' in spider research. I have scored the article for taxonomic error because Nephila pilipes is spelled wrong (it reads as 'filipes'). Grouping spiders with insects is another error. The spider shown in the photo is not a Nephila but since there is no caption, I haven't scored it for error figures. Although it isn't sensational in the usual way I've scored it for sensationalism because it claims that there are many instances of fingers 'rotting' due to spider bites, and that spiders have been identified as the cause of many deaths.

Title: Beyond the south,Tarantula panic now attacks the north
Notes: Report about fear of tarantulas spreading from south to north Bengal. A resident found a large black hairy fast-moving spider in his garden, which he identified as the same type of tarantula he'd just seen on TV. The local high school biology teacher (it's not clear whether he is an arachnologist) said the spider in the photo looked like a tarantula but he wouldn't give an ID based only on the photo. He advised staying far from the spider, since tarantulas have venom, and even though their bite may not kill, it would cause harm. Though the story is about local panic, no exaggerated claims are made by the writer and the tone is quite restrained.
